These lists are from Wikipedia and they are a list of both the male and female current olympic records in the track and field events. Each case represents a different event and then has the current record and the athlete who currently hold that record. The tablelist 1 is the male records and the tablelist 2 is the female records.

Data Wrangling

Regular Expression of Olympic Records table

#label appropriate tables
malerecords<- tableList[[1]]
femalerecords<- tableList[[2]]
#filter male records 
malerecords <- 
  malerecords %>%
    filter(grepl(pattern = "\\d*metres$", Event)) %>%
    mutate(Record = ms(Record)) %>%
    mutate(Sex = "M")
malerecords
#filter female records 
femalerecords <-
  femalerecords %>%
    filter(grepl(pattern = "\\d*metres$", Event)) %>%
    mutate(Record = ms(Record)) %>%
    mutate(Sex = "F")
femalerecords

This was done to filter both the male and female records to only keep the records that have metres in that specific event. This made it easier to convert the times into something that we could use for the research question.

Joining Two Data Tables

#join sprinting records

Using Data Verbs on primary data set

#fitting the data to match our needs for the research question
olympicAthleteData <-
  olympicAthleteData%>%
  select(Name, Sex, Age, Team, Year, Sport, Event, Medal)%>%
  filter(Sport == "Athletics") %>%
  mutate(Name = as.character(Name),
         Sex = as.character(Sex),
         Sport = as.character(Sport),
         Event = as.character(Event),
         Medal = as.character(Medal),
         Team = as.character(Team)) %>%
  filter(grepl(pattern = "\\d*metres$", Event)) %>%
  mutate(Event = (gsub(pattern = "Athletics Women's|Athletics Men's", replacement = "", Event))) %>%
  rename("Athlete(s)" = Name) %>%
  rename("Nation" = Team)

olympicAthleteData

Since our research question is looking at if countries perform better than others in Track and Field at the olympics, we didnt need all of the information that the data table provided. For example, we only kept the athletes whose sport was Athletics, which is the sport for Track and Field in the Olympics. We kept filtering out unnecessary data until we were left with only the athletes that competed in the events that we had records for.

Using Data verbs on secondary data set

#fitting the records data table to match the olympic data table
SprintingRecords <-
  SprintingRecords %>%
  select(Event, Record, Nation, Date, `Athlete(s)`, Sex) %>%
  mutate(Date = mdy(Date),
         Year = year(Date)) %>%
  select(Event, Record, Nation, Year, `Athlete(s)`, Sex) %>%
  mutate(Nation = (gsub(pattern = "\\(.{3}\\)$", replacement = "", Nation))) %>%
  mutate(Medal = "Gold")

completeOlympicData

This was an important set in the wrangling process because it was the set the final data table that would be used for making our glyph ready data. This table combined the different countries, records, metals, and athletes that were needed to explain the research question.

Making the data glyph ready

#making glyph ready data
AthleteCounts <-
completeOlympicData %>%
  group_by(Nation, Sex) %>%
  summarise(count = n()) %>%
  spread(key = Sex, value = count) %>%
  mutate(TotalAthletes = F + M) %>%
  arrange(desc(TotalAthletes)) %>%
  na.omit()
AthleteCounts

MedalCounts <-
  completeOlympicData %>%
    group_by(Nation, Medal) %>%
    summarise(count = n()) %>%
    spread (key = Medal, value = count) %>%
    mutate(TotalMedals = sum(Bronze + Gold + Silver)) %>%
    select(Bronze, Gold, Silver, TotalMedals) %>% 
    arrange(desc(TotalMedals)) %>%
    na.omit()
Adding missing grouping variables: `Nation`
MedalCounts

Counts <-
  MedalCounts %>%
    left_join(AthleteCounts)
Joining, by = "Nation"
Counts

With this data table, each of the countries are its own case. With the variables of metal counts fpr each metal- gold, silver, and bronze, and also the total counts of the total athletes that have competed from each country. With this data we will be able to look at total metal counts by country and see how metal counts compared to the number of athletes that the countries send to the Olympics.

Graphics

Bar Graphs

#athlete counts by country 
AthleteCounts%>%
  filter(TotalAthletes > 200)%>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Nation, y = TotalAthletes))+
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", aes(fill = Nation))+
  labs(title = "Athlete Counts by Nation")

This bar graph makes it clear to see that some countries send a lot more athletes to the Olympics compared to other countries. The United States and Great Britain send hundreds more athletes to the Olympics when compared to countries like Spain or Sweden.

#medal counts by country
MedalCounts%>%
  filter(TotalMedals > 20) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Nation, y = TotalMedals)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", aes(fill = Nation)) +
  labs(title = "Medal Counts by Country")

This bar graph demonstrates that there are certainly countries that have earned more medals in Track and Field events than others. The United States has clearly earned the most medals, but other countries that have performed well in Track and Field at the Olympics are Great Britain, Kenya, and Jamaica.

#gold medal counts by country
MedalCounts%>%
  filter(TotalMedals > 20) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Nation, y = Gold)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", aes(fill = Nation)) +
  labs(title = "Gold Medal Counts by Country")

When we investigate the counts of just the gold medals, the top countries with the highest counts are pretty similar to the countries that earn the highest total counts of medals. The United States and Great Britain are still earn the highest two counts.

RecordCounts <-
  completeOlympicData %>%
  select(Nation, Event, Record) %>%
  filter(is.na(Record) == FALSE)

RecordCounts %>%
  group_by(Nation) %>%
  summarise(RecordCount= n()) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Nation, y = RecordCount)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", aes(fill = Nation)) +
  labs(title = "Record Counts by Country")

This graph shows that the countries with greater counts of track and field athletes do not necessarily perform the best in track and field events. Ethiopia and Kenya currently have the most athletes holding records in sprinting events, yet their athlete counts are small in comparison to countries like the United States and Great Britain. The United States also has athletes who hold records in sprinting events, but Great Britain, the nation with the second highest count of sprinting athletes, does not currently hold any records for those events.

Scatter Plot

#Metal counts compared to athlete counts by nation
Counts %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = TotalAthletes, y = TotalMedals)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color = Nation)) + 
  geom_smooth(method = lm) +
  theme(legend.position = "right") + 
  labs(title = "Athlete Counts vs. Medal Counts by Nation")

This scatterplot demonstrates that countries with more total track and field athletes tend to earn more total medals. The linear model has a wide confidence band, so the relationship between total athletes and total medals is probably not modelled best by a linear relationship. There are most likely other variables that contribute more significantly to the number of medals that a nation earns.

Conclusion

When observing the different graphics of the data, it is very clear to see that some countries do perform better than others. This can be seen when loking at the graphs that look at the total metal counts by each country. The United States has significantly more metals when compared to other countries, followed by Great Britain anf then Kenya. However, there seems to be a relationship between the number of athletes a country sends to the Olympics and the number of metals they receive. For example, the United States has sent more athletes to the Olympics than any other country and they have received the most metals. The same goes for Great Britain who sent the second most athletes to the Olympics, and received the second most metals. This can also be observed in the athlete count verus metal count graph, there is a linear trend that can be determined; giving the expression that as a country sends more athletes to the Olympics, they will receive more metals as a country. However, this relationship between the number of athletes a country sends to the Olympics doesnt appear to apply to the records of the Olympics. The two countries tied with the most records are Ethiopia and Kenya, neither of which are in the top 5 countries for number of athletes sent to the Olympics.
